      Blue Owl
   =20
 =20
A sneakily important fact of finance is that if you make $10 million a year=
, you make $10 million a year, but if you own a company that makes $10 mill=
ion a year, it=E2=80=99s worth at least, say, $100 million. A stream of=C2=
=A0income is worth some multiple of a year=E2=80=99s income, depending on t=
hings like interest rates and how risky the income is and how much it is ex=
pected to grow; I am going to use a multiple of 10x for simplicity but real=
 numbers will vary. (The price/earnings ratio of the S&P 500 index right no=
w is about 29.6x; a company with that multiple and a $10 million annual net=
 income would be worth $296 million.)This means that if you are in some mon=
ey-making business, it might be a good idea to sell a portion of your busin=
ess. If you make $10 million a year, and the right multiple on your earning=
s is 10 times, then you own a $100 million business. If you sell 20% of tha=
t business to someone else, then that gets you several benefits:=09You have=
 $20 million=C2=A0to spend on houses, boats, etc., right now. (Of course, n=
ow you only get $8 million a year from your business; the buyer gets the ot=
her $2 million. But you get more money=C2=A0now.)=C2=A0=09You are=C2=A0rich=
er=C2=A0than you were. Before you sold a stake, you were making $10 million=
 a year; presumably you put some of that in the bank etc., but you were als=
o paying taxes and stuff and it would take many years=C2=A0for you to accum=
ulate $100 million. Now you have $20 million, and an 80% stake in a $100 mi=
llion business; your net worth is $100 million more than it was. Of course =
this isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0true; before selling the stake, you owned 100% of t=
his same business, which was presumably worth=C2=A0$100 million. But no one=
 is quite going to believe you that it=E2=80=99s a $100 million business=C2=
=A0until you sell the stake; selling the stake is what validates it as a $1=
00 million business and makes you a centimillionaire. In particular, sellin=
g a minority stake of a business is a traditional way to become =E2=80=9Ca =
billionaire=E2=80=9D: You have some high-eight-figure-ish annual income wit=
h good prospects for more,[1] you are rich but not a billionaire, but then =
you package that income into a company and sell a minority stake at a billi=
on-dollar valuation and, bam, you get the =E2=80=9Cbillionaire=E2=80=9D tit=
le.[2] None of this is economically important =E2=80=94=C2=A0the income str=
eam is what it is, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it can be psychologically import=
ant.=09You have taken some risk off the table: If the business crashes tomo=
rrow, you don=E2=80=99t get your $10 million (or $8 million) a year anymore=
, but you get to keep the $20 million. Your new co-owner shares the risk of=
 the business with you.=09You save on taxes. Probably the $10 million a yea=
r that you were making before was taxed as ordinary income, at relatively h=
igh rates. But when you sell 20% of your business for $20 million, that's c=
apital gains: That's not income for your labor (taxed at high rates), but r=
ather an increase in the value of stock that you own in your business (taxe=
d at lower rates).[3] By selling a stake in your business you get to transm=
ute ordinary income into capital gains.[4]This is very straightforward stuf=
f, but it is=C2=A0finance-y stuff; it is stuff that not everyone knows or t=
hinks about. So there is a business of just going around to people who run =
their own prosperous businesses=C2=A0and telling them this. You run a priva=
te equity firm, you go to family businesses or doctors' practices or whatev=
er, you say =E2=80=9Chey you could work for the next 10 years and get paid =
for your work and pay taxes on your income, or you could sell a portion of =
that income to us in advance, get money now, save on taxes, and mark your w=
ealth to market so you can tell people that you=E2=80=99re really rich.=E2=
=80=9D And the doctors or whoever are like =E2=80=9Chuh I never thought of =
that, give me the money,=E2=80=9D and you=E2=80=99ve got a good trade. The =
tax advantages alone =E2=80=94=C2=A0converting future ordinary income into =
present capital gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0can make it a good deal for both sides=
.One thing is that, if you do run a private equity firm that does this sort=
 of trade, a lot of your income comes in the form of recurring management f=
ees on the private equity funds that you run. These fees are taxed as ordin=
ary income, and the main purpose of most private equity managers' lives is =
to turn ordinary income into capital gains.[5] Another life purpose=C2=A0is=
 of course becoming a billionaire. And so you might look around and say =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0wait a minute, I am buying stakes in family businesses so their=
 owners can get nominally richer and optimize their taxes; who will buy a s=
take in=C2=A0my=C2=A0business so I can be nominally richer and optimize my =
taxes?And the answer is Michael Rees:Until Michael Rees became a billionair=
e this year, he was arguably the most popular man on Wall Street. ...In lit=
tle more than a decade the firm that Rees co-owned, Dyal Capital, has paid =
out well over $10bn to buy minority stakes in some of the best-performing c=
ompanies in finance. He has forked out hundreds of millions of dollars to t=
he founders of private equity firms including Silver Lake and Providence Eq=
uity; to hedge fund managers including Jana Capital; and to firms such as G=
olub Capital and Owl Rock, which are displacing banks as chief lenders to a=
 swath of corporate America.That is from this delightful Financial Times pr=
ofile of Rees and Dyal, which =E2=80=9Cgives top financiers a way to conver=
t their paper fortunes into cash and potentially lower their tax bills.=E2=
=80=9DBut then if you are Michael Rees, and you are in the business of buyi=
ng stakes in private equity firms so their owners can get nominally richer =
and optimize their taxes, you might look around and say =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wait=
 a minute, who will buy a stake in=C2=A0my=C2=A0business so I can be nomina=
lly richer and optimize my taxes? And the answer is a complicated three-way=
 merger involving a special purpose acquisition company that allowed Dyal C=
apital to go public as part of Blue Owl Capital Inc.:This year Rees, 46, be=
came a billionaire in his own right. Having started Dyal in 2011 as an expe=
rimental division on the fringes of asset manager Neuberger Berman, he brok=
e free of his parent company and pulled off a $12bn transaction that amount=
s to one of the biggest ever stock market debuts by a US private capital gr=
oup. The enlarged company, known as Blue Owl, instantly achieved a market c=
apitalisation close to that of Carlyle Group, Ares Management and other mor=
e established rivals.He =E2=80=9Cbecame a billionaire=E2=80=9D in this stri=
ctly nominal sense: He had a stream of income before, and he has that strea=
m of income now, but having sold a stake in it at a multibillion-dollar val=
uation, now=C2=A0he=E2=80=99s a billionaire.Anyway the Blue Owl deal was ho=
tly controversial because, if you are an alternative investment manager in =
the business of taking minority stakes in alternative investment managers, =
eventually there are going to be conflicts of interest. Specifically, Dyal =
owned stakes in a couple of private credit funds called Sixth Street Capita=
l and Golub Capital, and the three-way merger that created Blue Owl involve=
d not just a SPAC but also another private credit fund named Owl Rock:Even =
some executives close to the deal acknowledge it appears rife with conflict=
.A Dyal fund had previously invested $500m in Owl Rock, before it merged wi=
th Dyal. It meant that Rees and Ward were now managing a fund that is also =
one of the biggest shareholders in their own firm. While the investors in D=
yal=E2=80=99s funds are still waiting for an opportunity to cash out, the s=
tock market listing has already given Rees and Ward big payouts of their ow=
n.The sharpest objections came from executives at Sixth Street and Golub Ca=
pital, who were unhappy that Dyal =E2=80=94 one of their biggest shareholde=
rs =E2=80=94 was merging with Owl Rock, one of their most formidable rivals=
. They characterised the transaction as a =E2=80=9Cbetrayal=E2=80=9D that w=
ould put their confidential financial information in the hands of a competi=
tor. And insisted that their deal with Dyal gave them a power of veto.It di=
d not.=C2=A0Golub and Sixth Street sued, claiming that transfer restriction=
s in their contract with Dyal prevented Dyal from merging; Delaware and New=
 York courts disagreed. Also the worries about betrayal do not seem particu=
larly real; the Delaware court found that =E2=80=9Cthis litigation and the =
parallel action in New York were part and parcel of a calculated effort to =
=E2=80=98muck up=E2=80=99 the Transaction to force a buyback=E2=80=9D of Dy=
al=E2=80=99s stakes in Golub and Sixth Street on cheap terms:After learning=
 of the Transaction, in December 2020, Sixth Street=E2=80=99s senior execut=
ives assured their investors that the Transaction would have =E2=80=9Czero =
impact on our business=E2=80=9D because Dyal III was a =E2=80=9Ccompletely =
passive investor=E2=80=9D run by =E2=80=9Cgood folks.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And imp=
ortantly, they emphasized that Dyal =E2=80=9C[does not] get competitively s=
ensitive information from us in any real sense,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and that =E2=
=80=9Cwhatever information they [Dyal] get will be manag[ed]=E2=80=9D with =
=E2=80=9Cinformational firewalls.=E2=80=9D Accordingly, David Stiepleman, S=
ixth Street=E2=80=99s Co-President and Chief Operating Officer, stated that=
 he was =E2=80=9Cnot particularly concerned about the theoretical possibili=
ty of [Owl Rock as] a smaller firm in the credit space seeing [Sixth Street=
=E2=80=99s] info.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Sixth Street reiterated its lack of concern=
 on multiple occasions, assuring=C2=A0investors that Dyal III was a =E2=80=
=9C[p]assive 10% owner of Sixth Street=E2=80=9D and there was =E2=80=9Cnoth=
ing [to be] concerned about at all=E2=80=9D with respect to the Transaction=
. =E2=80=A6Since filing, nothing in the record indicates Sixth Street ever =
actually became concerned about its confidential information. ...=C2=A0In h=
is deposition, Alan Waxman, Sixth Street=E2=80=99s CEO, testified that =E2=
=80=9C[Blue Owl is] not getting our pipeline. They=E2=80=99re not going to =
be involved in our investment process.=E2=80=9DIt=E2=80=99s good to sell a =
stake in your business to get cash and be rich, but the downside is that if=
 your business keeps growing, you have given up some of the upside. If you =
can buy it back cheap, you might as well try.
