      Tether
   =20
 =20
Here is the website for the JPMorgan Prime Money Market Fund. If you click =
on the tab labeled =E2=80=9Cportfolio,=E2=80=9D you can see what the fund o=
wns. The first item alphabetically is $50 million face amount of asset-back=
ed commercial paper issued by Alpine Securitization Corp. and maturing on O=
ct. 12. Its=C2=A0CUSIP =E2=80=94=C2=A0its official security identifier =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0is 02089XMG9. There are certificates of deposit at big banks, r=
epurchase agreements, even a little bit of non-financial commercial paper. =
The fund lends some money to LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton and Toyota Mo=
tor Finance (Netherlands) BV. You can see exactly how much (both face amoun=
t and market value), and when it matures, and the CUSIP for each holding.JP=
Morgan is not on the bleeding edge of transparency here or anything; this i=
s just how money market funds work. You disclose your holdings.Here is an i=
ncredible=C2=A0interview that the chief technology officer and general coun=
sel of Tether did yesterday with CNBC=E2=80=99s Deirdre Bosa.=C2=A0Tether i=
s a stablecoin that we have talked about around here  because it was=C2=A0s=
ued by the New York attorney general for lying about its reserves, and beca=
use it subsequently disclosed its reserves in a format that satisfied basic=
ally no one. Tether now says that its reserves consist mostly of commercial=
 paper,  which=C2=A0apparently=C2=A0makes it one of the largest commercial =
paper holders in the world. There is a fun game among  financial journalist=
s and other interested=C2=A0observers=C2=A0who try to find anyone who has a=
ctually traded commercial paper with Tether, or any of its actual holdings.=
 The game is hard! As far as I know, no one has ever won it, or even scored=
 a point; I have never seen anyone=C2=A0publicly identify=C2=A0a security t=
hat Tether holds or a counterparty that has traded commercial paper with it=
.Bosa, who had two Tether executives on her show, sensibly asked them about=
 it several times, but you can=E2=80=99t win the game that easily! =E2=80=
=9CWe don=E2=80=99t disclose our commercial partners, so that is quite impo=
rtant,=E2=80=9D says CTO Paolo Ardoino at around the 5-minute mark. =E2=80=
=9CGiven our portfolio composition in commercial paper, we believe that it =
is quite important to respect the privacy of the banking partners that we w=
ork with.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s not a thing! That=E2=80=99s not a thing a=
t all! Every money-market fund just lists all of its holdings, by size and =
issuer and CUSIP! Tether has broken new ground in the concept of commercial=
-paper privacy rights! But, why?Everything in this interview melted my brai=
n. Another favorite came at around the 13-minute mark, when GC Stuart Hoegn=
er says =E2=80=9Cwe maintain cash, for example, that is many multiples abov=
e our single biggest redemption thus far, as well as above our biggest 24-h=
our period of redemptions,=E2=80=9D which is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0not =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0that =E2=80=A6=C2=A0much? (Banks, for instance, are generally require=
d to have =E2=80=9Chigh-quality liquid assets=E2=80=9D sufficient for =E2=
=80=9Ca 30 calendar day liquidity stress scenario.=E2=80=9D) There is more =
here, including a promise that audited financials are =E2=80=9Conly months =
away.=E2=80=9D I do not watch a lot of 32-minute business-television interv=
iews but I found this one riveting.Elsewhere, here is a paper from Gary Gor=
ton and Jeffery Zhang on =E2=80=9CTaming Wildcat Stablecoins=E2=80=9D:Crypt=
ocurrencies are all the rage, but there is nothing new about privately prod=
uced money. The goal of private money is to be accepted at par with no ques=
tions asked. This did not occur during the Free Banking Era in the United S=
tates=E2=80=94a period that most resembles the current world of stablecoins=
. State-chartered banks in the Free Banking Era experienced panics, and the=
ir private monies made it very hard to transact because of fluctuating pric=
es. That system was curtailed by the National Bank Act of 1863, which creat=
ed a uniform national currency backed by U.S. Treasury bonds. Subsequent le=
gislation taxed the state-chartered banks=E2=80=99 paper currencies out of =
existence in favor of a single sovereign currency.The newest type of privat=
e money is now upon us=E2=80=94in the form of stablecoins like =E2=80=9CTet=
her=E2=80=9D and Facebook=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CDiem=E2=80=9D (formerly =E2=80=
=9CLibra=E2=80=9D). Based on lessons learned from history, we argue that pr=
ivately produced monies are not an effective medium of exchange because the=
y are not always accepted at par and are subject to runs. We present propos=
als to address the systemic risks created by stablecoins, including regulat=
ing stablecoin issuers as banks and issuing a central bank digital currency=
.I guess. I am skeptical about the systemic risks of stablecoins; I  wrote =
last month=C2=A0that =E2=80=9CI think of stablecoins as sort of the lobby o=
f the casino that is crypto speculation, and I assume that the main use of =
Tether is to take a quick break from betting on Bitcoin without actually le=
aving the casino.=E2=80=9D If that=E2=80=99s the main use case then the wor=
st thing that happens, in a run on Tether, is that a bunch of gamblers lose=
 their money; that is bad for them but I am not sure how it is a=C2=A0syste=
mic=C2=A0problem. As Byrne Hobart writes: =E2=80=9CCrypto is incredibly wel=
l-contained,=C2=A0in that there are giant companies that do crypto (and alm=
ost nothing else), and there are giant companies with massively diversified=
 portfolios that have a tiny slice of crypto.=E2=80=9D There may be systemi=
c risks=C2=A0within crypto, but it=E2=80=99s hard to see how they could be =
systemic risks to the rest of the economy.Also, on the claim that =E2=80=9C=
privately produced monies are not an effective medium of exchange because t=
hey are not always accepted at par and are subject to runs,=E2=80=9D CoinMa=
rketCap tells me that Tether has traded between $0.9996 and $1.0009 over th=
e last seven days, including during yesterday=E2=80=99s interview. That=E2=
=80=99s a pretty tight range given that, you know, anyone can watch the int=
erview.


