      Elon Musk=C2=A0Cathie Wood=C2=A0Bitcoin=C2=A0Dogecoin
   =20
 =20
One thing about Elon Musk is that he runs Tesla Inc., and also Space Explor=
ation Technologies Corp., and also the Boring Co., and also a direct-to-con=
sumer clothing retailer, and also a tequila business, and also he=E2=80=99s=
 very rich in his personal account. Another thing about Elon Musk is that w=
hen he buys (or sells) Bitcoin (or Dogecoin), people rush to copy him, and =
the price of Bitcoin (or Dogecoin) goes up (or down). He can combine these =
two facts to really precisely fine-tune the price of Bitcoin. If he wants B=
itcoin to go up, he can  say that Tesla is buying it. If it goes up too hig=
h, he can  say that Tesla isn=E2=80=99t buying it anymore. If then it goes =
down too low, he can say that SpaceX is buying it. If he wants to nudge it =
just a touch higher he can say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re now accepting Bitcoin=
 as payment for our short shorts.=E2=80=9D  Et cetera:Speaking at =E2=80=9C=
The B Word=E2=80=9D conference hosted by the Crypto Council for Innovation,=
 Musk discussed the outlook for Bitcoin with fellow backers Cathie Wood, he=
ad of Ark Investment Management, and Jack Dorsey, chief executive officer o=
f Twitter Inc. and Square Inc.Musk said that he personally owns Bitcoin, Et=
hereum and Dogecoin, while Tesla and SpaceX both exclusively own Bitcoin. T=
he cryptocurrency climbed as high as $32,820 during the panel Wednesday bef=
ore falling to about $31,683 at 3:49 p.m. New York time.Great, super, that=
=E2=80=99s fantastic. I look forward to his next panel:Musk: I bought some =
Dogecoin in a college savings account for my child  Ethan, I mean, X =C3=86=
 A-Xii.Dogecoin: [goes up to $0.76]Musk: But Tesla will not=C2=A0accept it =
as payment for our tequila.Dogecoin: [goes down to $0.61]Musk: Also the Bor=
ing Co. will start digging Dogecoin mines.Dogecoin: [goes up to $0.72]Musk:=
 But my brother Kimbal has been selling Dogecoin.Dogecoin: [goes down to $0=
.68]Musk: But my ex-wife=E2=80=99s cousin=E2=80=99s nephew bought some.Doge=
coin: [goes up to $0.69]Musk: Nice.I have  said before that Musk=C2=A0could=
=C2=A0do this as a profit-making enterprise: Buy Dogecoin, say he=E2=80=99d=
 bought Dogecoin, watch the price go up, sell Dogecoin, say he=E2=80=99d so=
ld Dogecoin, watch the price go down, repeat indefinitely. But it=E2=80=99s=
 fairly clear that, except occasionally by accident, that=E2=80=99s not wha=
t he=E2=80=99s doing. He=E2=80=99s not whipsawing the price of Bitcoin or D=
ogecoin=C2=A0for profit. He doesn=E2=80=99t need profit. He=E2=80=99s the r=
ichest or second-richest person on Earth, depending on who=E2=80=99s in spa=
ce that day, and he supposedly doesn=E2=80=99t like possessions. He likes=
=C2=A0trolling people online; that=E2=80=99s why he=E2=80=99s whipsawing th=
e price of Bitcoin and Dogecoin.Or as he  put it yesterday:=E2=80=9CI would=
 like to see Bitcoin succeed,=E2=80=9D Musk said. =E2=80=9CIf the price of =
Bitcoin goes down, I lose money. I might pump but don=E2=80=99t dump.=E2=80=
=9DIt=E2=80=99s in his economic interests to make the price of Bitcoin go u=
p, and he also has fun doing it, but sometimes it=E2=80=99s also fun to mak=
e it go down instead.Also at that conference, by the way:Wood said corporat=
ions should consider adding Bitcoin to their balance sheets, partly as a he=
dge against deflation.I feel like there=E2=80=99s been a decade of Bitcoin =
evangelists saying that Bitcoin is a good inflation hedge, since there is a=
 finite cap on the number of Bitcoins while the Federal Reserve can print b=
lah blah blah blah blah. But nope:Bitcoin=E2=80=99s steep selloff is underc=
utting the argument made by the digital currency=E2=80=99s proponents that =
it=E2=80=99s an inflation hedge. ...Bitcoin=E2=80=99s supporters for years =
have touted it as an inflation hedge like gold, mainly because the bitcoin =
network has a set limit on the number of units that can be created: 21 mill=
ion. Their argument hadn=E2=80=99t previously been tested, however, because=
 inflation has largely been under the Federal Reserve=E2=80=99s 2% target s=
ince bitcoin=E2=80=99s 2009 launch.Now for the first time in years, shortag=
es of semiconductors, lumber and workers are putting pressure on consumer p=
rices, sparking worries about inflation. At the same time, governments and =
central banks have been forced to spend trillions to prop up their economie=
s, potentially sapping the purchasing power of their currencies.The consume=
r-price index rose to 5.4% in June, its fastest pace in 13 years. And infla=
tion measures in 49 countries have all been rising since the beginning of t=
he year, according to the Center for Financial Stability, a New York-based =
nonprofit think tank.Bitcoin is going in the other direction. The digital c=
urrency has fallen in five of the past seven days and is down 7.9% in July,=
 extending its monthslong selloff. It is now up 10% in 2021.But if it=E2=80=
=99s not a good inflation hedge then it's a good deflation hedge, I guess t=
hat=E2=80=99s how finance works, why not.
