      Things happen
   =20
 =20
Deutsche Bank  Raises Pay for Juniors to Keep Up With Rivals.=C2=A0UBS  Lif=
ts Junior Bankers=E2=80=99 Pay, Following Rivals on Wall Street.=C2=A0The I=
nelastic Markets Hypothesis. Wall Street banks redirect China IPOs to Hong =
Kong after Didi shock. China Weighs  Unprecedented Penalty for Didi After U=
.S. IPO. Assets in Ant Group=E2=80=99s Flagship Money-Market Fund Drop to 2=
016 Levels. The Saudi Prince of Oil Prices Vows to Drill =E2=80=98Every Las=
t Molecule.=E2=80=99=C2=A0AMC Names CEO Adam Aron as Chairman. States Annou=
nce $26 Billion Settlement to Resolve Opioid Lawsuits. Evergrande shares ju=
mp as developer says spat with bank resolved. Tom Barrack Held Forth on Tru=
mp, Real Estate Just  Days Before Arrest. Fraud on the Farm: How a baby-fac=
ed CEO turned a Farmville clone into a massive Ponzi scheme. =E2=80=9CHustl=
e bro populism.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Man Calling Libraries And Masturbating To A S=
upreme Court Opinion.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in han=
dy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or =
you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here=
. Thanks![1] Here I am mostly talking about normal=C2=A0cash-flowing busine=
sses, but of course another very traditional way to become a billionaire is=
 to start a tech company, lose money every year for a while, and then take =
the company public at like a $50 billion valuation. There the value is all =
in the uncertain future cash flows, not the current ones. Same core idea th=
ough.[2] Actually in 2018, Forbes awarded Kylie Jenner the =E2=80=9Cbillion=
aire=E2=80=9D title even though she *hadn=E2=80=99t* sold a stake in her bu=
siness, which at the time was making a nine-figure net income, and Felix Sa=
lmon got annoyed: =E2=80=9CShe has taken no outside investment at all, so t=
here=E2=80=99s no valuation at which anybody has bought into her company. F=
orbes has slapped an $800 million valuation onto Kylie Cosmetics, without a=
nybody doing any kind of diligence on it at all, and has declared that enti=
re sum to be part of Jenner=E2=80=99s present wealth.=E2=80=9D He was right=
 that the *traditional* =E2=80=9Cmechanism for turning future assets into p=
resent assets ... is called selling all or part of the corporate entity you=
 own.=E2=80=9D As an economic matter, selling a minority stake in a busines=
s shouldn=E2=80=99t change the value of the business, but as a a matter of =
*getting on lists of billionaires* I think Salmon was probably right.[3] Pr=
esumably you got the stock for $0, when you founded the business, so this i=
s all taxable gain.[4] Also, you don=E2=80=99t pay taxes on the $80 million=
 value of the business that you retain. This is good, first of all, for hav=
ing a high nominal net worth: If you make $10 million a year and pay 50% ta=
x, your wealth accrues by at most $5 million a year, but if you turn that i=
nto an 80% stake in a $100 million company your nominal wealth goes up by $=
80 million, even though you=E2=80=99d have to pay taxes (at a lower rate) i=
f you sold it.=C2=A0You get to point to your pretax rather than post-tax we=
alth, as it were. But also there *are* sometimes ways to extract this money=
 without paying taxes, along =E2=80=9Cbuy borrow die=E2=80=9D lines.=C2=A0[=
5] Most famously, private equity managers also get paid in =E2=80=9Ccarried=
 interest,=E2=80=9D which is taxed as capital gains, and everyone complains=
 about this =E2=80=9Ccarried interest loophole.=E2=80=9D Also, though, they=
 like to turn management fees (ordinary income) into carry (capital gains);=
 a classic method is the =E2=80=9Cmanagement fee waiver,=E2=80=9D which has=
 been controversial for like a decade.
