<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Blue Owl</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A sneakily important fact of finance i=
s that if you make $10 million a year, you make $10 million a year, but if =
you own a company that makes $10 million a year, it=E2=80=99s worth at leas=
t, say, $100 million. A stream of=C2=A0income is worth some multiple of a y=
ear=E2=80=99s income, depending on things like interest rates and how risky=
 the income is and how much it is expected to grow; I am going to use a mul=
tiple of 10x for simplicity but real numbers will vary. (The price/earnings=
 ratio of the S&amp;P 500 index right now is about 29.6x; a company with th=
at multiple and a $10 million annual net income would be worth $296 million=
.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This means that if you are in some money=
-making business, it might be a good idea to sell a portion of your busines=
s. If you make $10 million a year, and the right multiple on your earnings =
is 10 times, then you own a $100 million business. If you sell 20% of that =
business to someone else, then that gets you several benefits:</p><ol style=
=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have $20 million=C2=A0to spend on houses, =
boats, etc., right now. (Of course, now you only get $8 million a year from=
 your business; the buyer gets the other $2 million. But you get more money=
=C2=A0<em>now</em>.)=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are=
=C2=A0<em>richer=C2=A0</em>than you were. Before you sold a stake, you were=
 making $10 million a year; presumably you put some of that in the bank etc=
., but you were also paying taxes and stuff and it would take many years=C2=
=A0for you to accumulate $100 million. Now you have $20 million, and an 80%=
 stake in a $100 million business; your net worth is $100 million more than=
 it was. Of course this isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>true</em>; before selling th=
e stake, you owned 100% of this same business, which was presumably worth=
=C2=A0$100 million. But no one is quite going to <em>believe</em> you that =
it=E2=80=99s a $100 million business=C2=A0until you sell the stake; selling=
 the stake is what validates it as a $100 million business and makes you a =
centimillionaire. In particular, selling a minority stake of a business is =
a traditional way to become =E2=80=9Ca billionaire=E2=80=9D: You have some =
high-eight-figure-ish annual income with good prospects for more,[1] you ar=
e rich but not a billionaire, but then you package that income into a compa=
ny and sell a minority stake at a billion-dollar valuation and, bam, you ge=
t the =E2=80=9Cbillionaire=E2=80=9D title.[2] None of this is economically =
important =E2=80=94=C2=A0the income stream is what it is, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but it can be psychologically important.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">You have taken some risk off the table: If the business crashes t=
omorrow, you don=E2=80=99t get your $10 million (or $8 million) a year anym=
ore, but you get to keep the $20 million. Your new co-owner shares the risk=
 of the business with you.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You sav=
e on taxes. Probably the $10 million a year that you were making before was=
 taxed as ordinary income, at relatively high rates. But when you sell 20% =
of your business for $20 million, that's capital gains: That's not income f=
or your labor (taxed at high rates), but rather an increase in the value of=
 stock that you own in your business (taxed at lower rates).[3] By selling =
a stake in your business you get to transmute ordinary income into capital =
gains.[4]</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is very straightforwar=
d stuff, but it is=C2=A0<em>finance-</em>y stuff; it is stuff that not ever=
yone knows or thinks about. So there is a business of just going around to =
people who run their own prosperous businesses=C2=A0and <em>telling them th=
is</em>. You run a private equity firm, you go to family businesses or <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24525843.267046/aHR0cH=
M6Ly9yZXZjeWNsZWludGVsbGlnZW5jZS5jb20vbmV3cy9wcml2YXRlLWVxdWl0eS1maXJtcy1pb=
mNyZWFzaW5nbHktYnV5aW5nLXBoeXNpY2lhbi1wcmFjdGljZXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B0490d5c5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>doctors' practices</a> or whatever, you say =E2=80=9Chey you could work fo=
r the next 10 years and get paid for your work and pay taxes on your income=
, or you could sell a portion of that income to us in advance, get money no=
w, save on taxes, and mark your wealth to market so you can tell people tha=
t you=E2=80=99re really rich.=E2=80=9D And the doctors or whoever are like =
=E2=80=9Chuh I never thought of that, give me the money,=E2=80=9D and you=
=E2=80=99ve got a good trade. The tax advantages alone =E2=80=94=C2=A0conve=
rting future ordinary income into present capital gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0can =
make it a good deal for both sides.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thi=
ng is that, if you do run a private equity firm that does this sort of trad=
e, a lot of your income comes in the form of recurring management fees on t=
he private equity funds that you run. These fees are taxed as ordinary inco=
me, and the main purpose of most private equity managers' lives is to turn =
ordinary income into capital gains.[5] Another life purpose=C2=A0is of cour=
se becoming a billionaire. And so you might look around and say =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0wait a minute, I am buying stakes in family businesses so their owner=
s can get nominally richer and optimize their taxes; who will buy a stake i=
n=C2=A0<em>my=C2=A0</em>business so I can be nominally richer and optimize =
my taxes?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the answer is Michael Rees:</=
p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Until Michael Rees became a bill=
ionaire this year, he was arguably the most popular man on Wall Street. ...=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In little more than a decade the firm that=
 Rees co-owned, Dyal Capital, has paid out well over $10bn to buy minority =
stakes in some of the best-performing companies in finance. He has forked o=
ut hundreds of millions of dollars to the founders of private equity firms =
including Silver Lake and Providence Equity; to hedge fund managers includi=
ng Jana Capital; and to firms such as Golub Capital and Owl Rock, which are=
 displacing banks as chief lenders to a swath of corporate America.</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is from <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24525843.267046/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2=
NvbnRlbnQvZjYzYzI2MzYtODI5Yy00OGIxLTlhYmItMjg4NTEwY2JmODE2P3NoYXJlVHlwZT1ub=
25naWZ0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdd70ca66" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">this delightful Financial Times profile</a=
> of Rees and Dyal, which =E2=80=9Cgives top financiers a way to convert th=
eir paper fortunes into cash and potentially lower their tax bills.=E2=80=
=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then if you are Michael Rees, and y=
ou are in the business of buying stakes in private equity firms so their ow=
ners can get nominally richer and optimize their taxes, you might look arou=
nd and say =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wait a minute, who will buy a stake in=C2=A0<em>m=
y=C2=A0</em>business so I can be nominally richer and optimize my taxes? An=
d the answer is a complicated three-way merger involving a special purpose =
acquisition company that allowed Dyal Capital to go public as part of Blue =
Owl Capital Inc.:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This year Ree=
s, 46, became a billionaire in his own right. Having started Dyal in 2011 a=
s an experimental division on the fringes of asset manager Neuberger Berman=
, he broke free of his parent company and pulled off a $12bn transaction th=
at amounts to one of the biggest ever stock market debuts by a US private c=
apital group. The enlarged company, known as Blue Owl, instantly achieved a=
 market capitalisation close to that of Carlyle Group, Ares Management and =
other more established rivals.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>He =E2=80=9Cbecame a billionaire=E2=80=9D in this strictly nominal sense: =
He had a stream of income before, and he has that stream of income now, but=
 having sold a stake in it at a multibillion-dollar valuation, <em>now=C2=
=A0</em>he=E2=80=99s a billionaire.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway =
the Blue Owl deal was hotly controversial because, if you are an alternativ=
e investment manager in the business of taking minority stakes in alternati=
ve investment managers, eventually there are going to be conflicts of inter=
est. Specifically, Dyal owned stakes in a couple of private credit funds ca=
lled Sixth Street Capital and Golub Capital, and the three-way merger that =
created Blue Owl involved not just a SPAC but also another private credit f=
und named Owl Rock:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even some e=
xecutives close to the deal acknowledge it appears rife with conflict.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A Dyal fund had previously invested $500m in Ow=
l Rock, before it merged with Dyal. It meant that Rees and Ward were now ma=
naging a fund that is also one of the biggest shareholders in their own fir=
m. While the investors in Dyal=E2=80=99s funds are still waiting for an opp=
ortunity to cash out, the stock market listing has already given Rees and W=
ard big payouts of their own.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The sharpest =
objections came from executives at Sixth Street and Golub Capital, who were=
 unhappy that Dyal =E2=80=94 one of their biggest shareholders =E2=80=94 wa=
s merging with Owl Rock, one of their most formidable rivals. They characte=
rised the transaction as a =E2=80=9Cbetrayal=E2=80=9D that would put their =
confidential financial information in the hands of a competitor. And insist=
ed that their deal with Dyal gave them a power of veto.</p></blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It did not.=C2=A0Golub and Sixth Street sued, cla=
iming that transfer restrictions in their contract with Dyal prevented Dyal=
 from merging; Delaware and New York courts disagreed. Also the worries abo=
ut betrayal do not seem particularly real; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/24525843.267046/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3VydHMuZGVsYXdhcmUuZ2=
92L09waW5pb25zL0Rvd25sb2FkLmFzcHg_aWQ9MzE5MjYw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB084=
6d7b6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the=
 Delaware court found</a> that =E2=80=9Cthis litigation and the parallel ac=
tion in New York were part and parcel of a calculated effort to =E2=80=98mu=
ck up=E2=80=99 the Transaction to force a buyback=E2=80=9D of Dyal=E2=80=99=
s stakes in Golub and Sixth Street on cheap terms:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After learning of the Transaction, in December 2020, S=
ixth Street=E2=80=99s senior executives assured their investors that the Tr=
ansaction would have =E2=80=9Czero impact on our business=E2=80=9D because =
Dyal III was a =E2=80=9Ccompletely passive investor=E2=80=9D run by =E2=80=
=9Cgood folks.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And importantly, they emphasized that Dyal =E2=
=80=9C[does not] get competitively sensitive information from us in any rea=
l sense,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and that =E2=80=9Cwhatever information they [Dyal] g=
et will be manag[ed]=E2=80=9D with =E2=80=9Cinformational firewalls.=E2=80=
=9D Accordingly, David Stiepleman, Sixth Street=E2=80=99s Co-President and =
Chief Operating Officer, stated that he was =E2=80=9Cnot particularly conce=
rned about the theoretical possibility of [Owl Rock as] a smaller firm in t=
he credit space seeing [Sixth Street=E2=80=99s] info.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Sixth S=
treet reiterated its lack of concern on multiple occasions, assuring=C2=A0i=
nvestors that Dyal III was a =E2=80=9C[p]assive 10% owner of Sixth Street=
=E2=80=9D and there was =E2=80=9Cnothing [to be] concerned about at all=E2=
=80=9D with respect to the Transaction. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Since filing, nothing in the record indicates Sixth Street ever actu=
ally became concerned about its confidential information. ...=C2=A0In his d=
eposition, Alan Waxman, Sixth Street=E2=80=99s CEO, testified that =E2=80=
=9C[Blue Owl is] not getting our pipeline. They=E2=80=99re not going to be =
involved in our investment process.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s good to sell a stake in your business to get ca=
sh and be rich, but the downside is that if your business keeps growing, yo=
u have given up some of the upside. If you can buy it back cheap, you might=
 as well try.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellsp=
acing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
