yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">Taming Wildcat Stablecoins</a>=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Cryptocurrencies are all the rage, but there is n=
othing new about privately produced money. The goal of private money is to =
be accepted at par with no questions asked. This did not occur during the F=
ree Banking Era in the United States=E2=80=94a period that most resembles t=
he current world of stablecoins. State-chartered banks in the Free Banking =
Era experienced panics, and their private monies made it very hard to trans=
act because of fluctuating prices. That system was curtailed by the Nationa=
l Bank Act of 1863, which created a uniform national currency backed by U.S=
. Treasury bonds. Subsequent legislation taxed the state-chartered banks=E2=
=80=99 paper currencies out of existence in favor of a single sovereign cur=
rency.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The newest type of private money is =
now upon us=E2=80=94in the form of stablecoins like =E2=80=9CTether=E2=80=
=9D and Facebook=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CDiem=E2=80=9D (formerly =E2=80=9CLibra=
=E2=80=9D). Based on lessons learned from history, we argue that privately =
produced monies are not an effective medium of exchange because they are no=
t always accepted at par and are subject to runs. We present proposals to a=
ddress the systemic risks created by stablecoins, including regulating stab=
lecoin issuers as banks and issuing a central bank digital currency.</p></b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess. I am skeptical about the sy=
stemic risks of stablecoins; I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
